{"title_page": "Walsall F.C.", "text_new": "{{short description|Association football club}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2010}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = Walsall\n| current  = 2019\u201320 Walsall F.C. season\n| image    = Walsall FC.svg\n| image_size   = 150px\n| fullname = Walsall bad football club\n| nickname = The Saddlers , rubbish, terrible, so bad\n| founded  = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1888}}<br> (as ''Walsall Town Swifts'')\n| ground   = [[Bescot Stadium]]\n| capacity = 11,300\n| chairman = Leigh Pomlett\n| manager  = [[Darrell Clarke]] \n| league = {{English football updater|Walsall}}\n| season = {{English football updater|Walsall2}}\n| position = {{English football updater|Walsall3}}\n| website = http://www.saddlers.co.uk\n| pattern_la1   = _walsall1920h\n| pattern_b1    = _walsall1920h\n| pattern_ra1   = _walsall1920h\n| pattern_sh1   = _walsall1920h\n| pattern_so1   = _walsall1920h\n| leftarm1      = FF0000\n| body1         = FF0000\n| rightarm1     = FF0000\n| shorts1       = FFFFFF\n| socks1        = FF0000\n| pattern_la2   = _kobenhavn1819f\n| pattern_b2    = _walsall1920a\n| pattern_ra2   = _kobenhavn1819f\n| pattern_sh2   = _walsall1920a\n| pattern_so2   = _walsall1920a\n| leftarm2      = 000000\n| body2         = 000000\n| rightarm2     = 000000\n| shorts2       = 000000\n| socks2        = 000000\n| pattern_la3   = _walsall1920t\n| pattern_b3    = _walsall1920t\n| pattern_ra3   = _walsall1920t\n| pattern_sh3   = _walsall1920t\n| pattern_so3   = _walsall1920t\n| leftarm3      = 00FFEF\n| body3         = 00FFEF\n| rightarm3     = 00FFEF\n| shorts3       = 000000\n| socks3        = 00FFEF\n}}\n'''Walsall Football Club''' is a professional [[association football]] club based in the town of [[Walsall]], [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]], England. The team competes in {{English football updater|Walsall}}, the fourth tier of the [[English football league system]]. The club's nickname, \"The Saddlers\", reflects Walsall's status as a traditional centre for [[saddle]] manufacture. Walsall moved into their [[Bescot Stadium]] in 1990, having previously played at nearby [[Fellows Park]] for almost a century. The team play in a red and white kit and their club crest features a [[swift]]. They hold rivalries with nearby [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] and [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]], as well as farther away but more regularly contested rivalries with [[Coventry City]] ,[[Shrewsbury Town F.C.|Shrewsbury Town]] and [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]].\n\nThe club was founded in 1888 as '''Walsall Town Swifts''', an amalgamation of Walsall Town and Walsall Swifts.<ref name=\"HistoryBook\">{{Cite book|last=Matthews|first=Tony|title=The Complete Record of Walsall Football Club|publisher=Breedon Books|date=1999|isbn=978-1859831564}}</ref>{{rp|9}} The club moved to the [[Football Alliance]] from the Midland Association the following year, before being invited to help found the [[Football League Second Division]] in 1892. They failed re-election in 1895, but were elected back into the [[English Football League|Football League]] after one season in the [[Midland Football League (1889)|Midland League]]. They failed re-election again in 1901 and this time spent two decades outside the Football League, primarily in the [[Birmingham & District Football League|Birmingham & District League]]. Invited to help form the [[Football League Third Division North]] in 1921, they would remain in the third tier for the next 37 years before becoming founder members of the [[Football League Fourth Division|Fourth Division]]. Walsall won the Fourth Division title in 1959\u201360 and then secured promotion out of the [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] the following season, though were relegated in 1963 and again in 1979.\n\nWalsall won promotion out of the Fourth Division in 1979\u201380, but suffered two successive relegations after winning promotion into the Second Division at the end of the 1987\u201388 campaign. Promoted in 1994\u201395 and again in 1998\u201399, they spent four of the next five seasons in the second tier, punctuated by a successful third tier promotion campaign in 2000\u201301. Two relegations in three years left Walsall back in the fourth tier in 2006, but they secured an immediate promotion as 2006\u201307 [[EFL League Two|League Two]] champions. Their first match at [[Wembley Stadium]] came in the [[2015 Football League Trophy Final]], which they lost to [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]], and they ended an 11-year stay in [[EFL League One|League One]] with relegation in 2019.\n\n==History==\n{{See also|Walsall F.C. seasons}}\n\n===Formation and early years (1888\u20131939)===\n[[File:WalsallFC1893.jpg|thumb|right|300px|The Walsall team pictured in 1893]]\nWalsall were formed as '''Walsall Town Swifts F.C.''' in 1888 when Walsall Town F.C. and Walsall Swifts F.C. amalgamated.<ref name=\"social\">{{cite web|title=Walsall Social Life|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=36201|work=A History of the County of Stafford: Volume 17: Offlow hundred (part)|publisher=British History Online|accessdate=4 October 2010|editor=M Greenslade |year=1976}}</ref> Walsall Town had been founded in 1877 and Walsall Swifts in 1879.<ref name=social/> Both clubs had played at [[the Chuckery]], and the newly formed club remained at the same ground. Walsall Town Swifts' first match was a 0\u20130 draw against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in the Birmingham Charity Cup final on 9 April 1888. A disagreement over the venue of the replay meant Aston Villa were rewarded the trophy.<ref name=\"HistoryBook\"/>{{rp|7}}<ref>{{cite news|title=Walsall FC to host Aston Villa in 125th birthday bash|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/sport/football/walsall-fc/2013/05/18/walsall-fc-to-host-aston-villa-in-125th-birthday-bash//|date=13 May 2018|work=Express & Star|accessdate=23 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nLater that year, Walsall Town Swifts played friendly matches against two founder members of the [[Football League]]; a strong [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] side were beaten 1\u20130 and [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] were held to a 2\u20132 draw in front of 7,000 spectators at the Chuckery. Walsall's first league campaign in the Midland Association started with a 2\u20132 draw at home to [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]] on 22 September 1888. They went on to finish in 3rd place in the league.<ref name=\"HistoryBook\"/>{{rp|141}}\n\nThe club were first admitted to the [[The Football League|Football League]] in 1892, as founder members of the new [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]]. They moved to the [[West Bromwich Road]] ground in 1893 after complaints from local residents about them playing at the Chuckery. After finishing 14th out of 16 teams in [[1894\u201395 Football League|1894\u201395]] the club failed to be re-elected to the Football League. At the start of the 1895 season the club once again moved grounds, this time to [[Fellows Park]] which remained the club's home for over a century.\n\nIn 1896 the club changed their name to simply '''Walsall F.C.'''<ref name=social/> and joined the [[Midland League (1889)|Midland League]]. A year later, they returned to the Second Division. The team finished in 6th place in [[1898\u201399 Football League|1898\u201399]] in a season that, to this day, proves to be their highest ever league finish. Despite this relative success, the club once again failed re-election two years later and dropped back into the Midland League. A move to the [[Birmingham & District Football League|Birmingham League]] followed in 1903 and in 1910 the club were elected to the [[Southern Football League|Southern League]]. With the expansion of the Football League after [[World War I]], Walsall became a founding member of the [[Football League Third Division North|Third Division North]] in 1921 and have remained a [[Football League]] side ever since.\n\nWalsall's highest \"home\" attendance was set in 1930, when they played in of front of 74,646 fans in a 3\u20131 defeat to [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in the [[FA Cup]] fourth round.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.11v11.com/matches/aston-villa-v-walsall-25-january-1930-207839/|title=Aston Villa v Walsall, 25 January 1930|website=www.11v11.com|accessdate=10 October 2018}}</ref> Although a home match for Walsall, the tie was played at their opponents' [[Villa Park]] ground to ensure as many people could watch the local ''David vs Goliath'' match as possible. It remains the highest attendance that Walsall have ever played in front of and was a record crowd for Villa Park at the time.<ref name=\"HistoryBook\"/>{{rp|28}}\n\nIn the years from 1921 leading up to [[World War II]] Walsall's success remained limited, with finishes of 3rd in [[1922\u201323 Football League|1922\u201323]], 5th in [[1932\u201333 Football League|1932\u201333]] and 4th in [[1933\u201334 Football League|1933\u201334]] the closest the club came to achieving promotion. The decent results in the early 1930s were spearheaded by the emergence of one of Walsall's greatest ever players, [[Gilbert Alsop]], who scored a remarkable 169 goals between 1931 and 1935.<ref name=\"HistoryBook\"/>{{rp|29}}\n\nAlsop also inspired Walsall's finest ever FA Cup result, scoring the opening goal in a 2\u20130 home win against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in 1933. Arsenal were regarded as the best team in the country at the time and went on to win the [[Football League First Division|First Division]] that season and the two seasons following that.<ref name=\"HistoryBook\"/>{{rp|30\u201331}} As such, the cup defeat to Third Division North side Walsall is still regarded as one of the greatest upsets in FA Cup history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://angryofislington.com/2012/05/30/arsenal-v-walsall-1933-the-greatest-cup-upset-ever/|title=Arsenal v Walsall 1933: The Greatest Cup Upset Ever|website=www.angryofislington.com|accessdate=24 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thegiantkillers.co.uk/1933walsall.htm|title=Walsall 2\u20130 Arsenal|website=www.thegiantkillers.co.uk|publisher=Steve Porter|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the following season, [[1934\u201335 in English football|1934\u201335]], Walsall continued their cup pedigree by reaching their first ever senior final in the [[Football League Third Division North Cup|Third Division North Cup]]. ''The Saddlers'' fell at the final hurdle, however, with a 2\u20130 defeat to [[Stockport County]] at [[Maine Road]].<ref name=\"HistoryBook\"/>{{rp|178}}\n\n===Post-war era and first league title (1945\u20131980)===\n1945\u201346 signalled the final season of local war-time competitions. Between January and May 1946 the [[Football League Third Division South Cup|Third Division South Cup]] was contested as a pre-curser for the return of full-time league football later that year. Walsall reached the final to face [[A.F.C. Bournemouth|Bournemouth]] at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] but, in a repeat of their previous final appearance in 1935, they lost the match 2\u20130.<ref name=\"HistoryBook\"/>{{rp|189}}\n\nThe return of football following the war saw a spike in attendances for many clubs across the Football League and Walsall were no different. In the [[1947\u201348 in English football|1947\u201348]] season a number of impressive turnouts at Fellows Park, including a season-best 20,383 for the visit of [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]], saw the club record its highest average league attendance to date of 15,711.<ref name=\"HistoryBook\"/>{{rp|191}} In the same season Walsall finished in 3rd place but once again missed out on promotion to the Second Division.\n\nThe early 1950s saw some of Walsall's most troubling and dismal times in the Football League, as the club faced the [[Re-election (Football League)|re-election process]] four years in a row. They finished bottom of the league in [[1951\u201352 in English football|1951\u201352]], [[1952\u201353 in English football|1952\u201353]] and [[1953\u201354 in English football|1953\u201354]] and improved to only second bottom in [[1954\u201355 in English football|1954\u201355]]. The club, however, managed to retain its Football League status through this period, largely thanks to the high attendances at Fellows Park demonstrating a healthy desire for League football in Walsall.<ref name=\"HistoryBook\"/>{{rp|41\u201342}}\n\nIn 1958, following a reorganisation of the Football League, Walsall became founder members of the [[Football League Fourth Division|Fourth Division]] \u2014 now holding the distinction of having being founder members of the Second, Third and Fourth tiers. Under the management of [[Bill Moore (footballer)|Bill Moore]], the club achieved successive promotions, scoring 102 goals on their way to winning the Fourth Division title in [[1959\u201360 in English football|1959\u201360]] and finishing as Third Division runners-up in [[1960\u201361 in English football|1960\u201361]]. The league title in 1960 was the club's first in their 72-year history.\n\nIn the club's first season in the second tier of English football since the early 1900s a post-war record 14th-place finish was achieved.<ref name=\"HistoryBook\"/>{{rp|203\u2013205}} It was during this season that the club also recorded its record attendance, as 25,453 crammed into Fellows Park to see ''The Saddlers'' beat [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] 1\u20130 in August 1961.<ref name=\"HistoryBook\"/>{{rp|47}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.11v11.com/matches/walsall-v-newcastle-united-29-august-1961-110629/|title=Walsall v Newcastle United, 29 August 1961|website=www.11v11.com|accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref> However, after just two seasons in the Second Division, the club were relegated back to the Third Division in [[1962\u201363 in English football|1962\u201363]]. An unfortunate defeat to [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] in a replayed final match of the season sealed Walsall's relegation, as the London club leapfrogged them in the table to survive.<ref name=\"HistoryBook\"/>{{rp|47}}\n\nOne of Walsall's finest ever talents, [[Allan Clarke (footballer)|Allan Clarke]], made his breakthrough as a first team regular in the [[1964\u201365 in English football|1964\u201365]] season. Aged just 18, he scored 23 league goals in 1964\u201365 and a further 23 goals in all competitions in [[1965\u201366 in English football|1965\u201366]]. He was sold to First Division [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] for a then club record fee of \u00a337,500 in March 1966 and went on to earn 19 caps for [[England national football team|England]] and win a league title at [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.leeds-live.co.uk/sport/leeds-united/allan-clarke-leeds-united-centurions-15241349|title=Allan Clarke was the magnetising frontman of Don Revie\u2019s Leeds|date=31 July 2019|work=Leeds Live|accessdate=11 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"HistoryBook\"/>{{rp|98}}\n\n[[1970\u201371 in English football|1970\u201371]] saw the first league meeting between Walsall and their very first opponents Aston Villa. The two clubs met in the Third Division with Walsall winning the home tie 3\u20130, thanks to two goals from [[Geoff Morris (footballer, born 1949)|Geoff Morris]] and a [[Colin Taylor]] penalty. The away tie at Villa Park later in the season ended goalless.\n\nKen Wheldon, a local businessman made good, took over the club in 1972 and brought some optimism of a brighter future.<ref name=\"Wheldon\">{{cite web|url=http://twohundredpercent.net/100-owners-number-76-ken-wheldon-walsall-birmingham-city/|title=100 Owners: Number 76 \u2013 Ken Wheldon (Walsall & Birmingham City)|work=Two Hundred Percent|accessdate=6 August 2019}}</ref> The following years were inconsistent but were buoyed by a few good cup results and the emergence of [[Alan Buckley]], who signed for the club in 1973 and went on to become a prolific goalscorer for the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/player/alanbuckley.html|title=Alan Buckley|work=Post War English & Scottish Football League A\u2013Z Players Database|publisher=Neil Brown|accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref> Walsall remained in the Third Division until a further relegation to the Fourth Division in [[1978\u201379 in English football|1978\u201379]].\n\nIt was Buckley who took on the role of player-manager for the re-build in the fourth tier. Once again ''The Saddlers'' rose from the ashes of adversity as they secured an immediate promotion. At one stage in [[1979\u201380 in English football|1979\u201380]] Walsall recorded 21 consecutive matches without defeat, a record that still stands today. This saw the beginning of an era that became a hallmark for some of the most attractive football seen in Walsall as, under the guidance of Buckley, the side gradually established itself as promotion contenders in the Third Division.<ref name=\"HistoryBook\"/>{{rp|55}}\n\n===League Cup run, move to Bescot and the fourth tier (1980\u20131995)===\n[[File:Fellows Park - Geograph-2008825.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Walsall in action at Fellows Park in 1982]]\nWhile consolidating in the Third Division in the early 1980s, off-the-pitch issues took prominence throughout the decade. The dilapidated state of the club's Fellows Park home was becoming a problem and, in 1982, the intention to move in to [[groundshare]] [[Molineux Stadium|Molineux]] with [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] was announced by owner Ken Wheldon. The club's fans' quickly protested against the idea, as the ''Save Walsall Action Group'' was formed, and it never came to pass.<ref name=\"Wheldon\"/>\n\nThe [[1983\u201384 Football League Cup|1983\u201384 League Cup]] campaign was, arguably, Walsall's finest hour. After victories over [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]], [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] and local rivals [[Shrewsbury Town]], they defeated First Division club Arsenal 2\u20131 in the fourth round at [[Highbury Stadium|Highbury]]. A 4\u20132 victory over [[Rotherham United]] in the quarter-final saw ''The Saddlers'' advance to the semi-final to face holders and reigning First Division champions, [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]. An incredible 2\u20132 draw at [[Anfield]] in the first leg had Walsall dreaming of an unlikely cup final and place in Europe, however, a second leg 2\u20130 defeat in front of 19,591 at Fellows Park saw Walsall lose the tie 4\u20132 on aggregate.<ref name=\"Wembley\"/>\n\nBy 1986 further plans were announced to groundshare with one of the club's local rivals. This time it was at [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]]'s [[St Andrew's (stadium)|St Andrew's]] ground. The ''Save Walsall Action Group'' was again pressed into action and, after peaceful protests and the support of the local press, the Football League blocked the move.<ref name=\"Wheldon\"/> Walsall were subsequently bought by millionaire entrepreneur and racehorse owner [[Terry Ramsden]]<ref name=\"Ramsden\">{{cite news|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/sport/football/walsall-fc/2012/06/15/ex-walsall-owner-terry-ramsden-back-at-the-races/|title=Ex-Walsall owner Terry Ramsden back at the races|date=15 June 2012|work=Express & Star|accessdate=11 August 2019}}</ref> and with his money came high-profile signings and the attention of the national media. In [[1986\u201387 in English football|1986\u201387]], under new manager [[Tommy Coakley]], Walsall narrowly missed out on the play-offs but made considerable progress in the FA Cup as they defeated First Division Charlton Athletic and Birmingham City and took [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] to two replays in the fifth round.\n\n[[File:Walsall FC League Performance.svg|thumb|left|300px|Chart of table positions of Walsall in the Football League.]]Walsall finally earned promotion to the Second Division for the first time since 1963 by winning the Third Division [[1988 Football League play-offs|play-offs in 1988]]. [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] were beaten 4\u20130 in a replayed final at Fellows Park thanks to a [[David Kelly (association footballer)|David Kelly]] hattrick. However, the [[1988\u201389 in English football|1988\u201389 season]] saw the club immediately relegated from the Second Division and Ramsden's business empire collapse.<ref name=\"Ramsden\"/> Walsall were minutes from going out of business but survived, again through the actions of the supporters and local businessmen. A second successive relegation followed at the end of [[1989\u201390 in English football|1989\u201390]] as Walsall were consigned to the Fourth Division once again.\n\nThe club moved to the [[Bescot Stadium]] in 1990.<ref name=\"Bescot\">{{cite news|title=25 years at Bescot: The stadium that changed Walsall's fortunes|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/sport/2015/08/18/25-years-at-bescot-the-stadium-that-changed-clubs-fortunes/|work=Express and Star|date=18 August 2015|accessdate=9 August 2019}}</ref> At the time it was a state-of-the-art arena and was only the second new Football League ground since the 1950s.<ref name=\"Bescot\"/> The arrival at Bescot Stadium saw some stability brought back to the club after two successive relegations and the club was taken over by Jeff Bonser in 1991.<ref name=\"Bonser\">{{cite news|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/sport/football/walsall-fc/2019/07/29/comment-bonser-saved-saddlers-and-boosted-bonsers-savings/|title=Jeff Bonser saved Walsall and boosted his savings|date=29 July 2019|work=Express & Star|accessdate=6 August 2019}}</ref> [[Kenny Hibbitt]] managed the club for four years, setting the groundwork for a golden era for the club that would follow soon after his dismissal in September 1994.\n\nNew manager [[Chris Nicholl]] led the club to promotion back to the third tier (now known as Division Two after the formation of the [[Premier League]]) in his first season, building the nucleus of a strong and under-rated team. A run of four straight wins at the end of April meant Walsall needed just a point from their final game, away to [[Bury F.C.|Bury]], to secure promotion; they duly obliged with a 0\u20130 scoreline to send the travelling fans home celebrating.<ref name=\"HistoryBook\"/>{{rp|66}}\n\n===A series of ups and downs (1995\u2013present)===\nTwo seasons of stability followed back in Division Two before Nicholl resigned. [[Jan S\u00f8rensen]] took the helm after Nicholl's departure and lead the club to the fourth round of both the League Cup and FA Cup in [[1997\u201398 in English football|1997\u201398]]. Each run was ended away to a Premier League side as [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] won 4\u20131 in the League Cup<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-lampard-hat-trick-announces-arrival-1295157.html|title=Lampard hat-trick announces arrival|date=20 November 1997|work=The Independent|accessdate=6 August 2019}}</ref> and a glamour tie at [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] resulted in a 5\u20131 defeat in the FA Cup.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-cole-and-solskjaer-the-perfect-partnership-1140938.html|title=Cole and Solskjaer the perfect partnership|date=26 January 1998|work=The Independent|accessdate=6 August 2019}}</ref> Despite the club's cup exploits, a poor finish in the league signalled the end of S\u00f8rensen's time at Walsall after just one season.\n\nIn [[1998\u201399 in English football|1998\u201399]], [[Ray Graydon]] took over as manager and led the club to a runners-up spot in Division Two, beating [[Manchester City]] to an automatic promotion place by five points.<ref name=\"Promotion 1999\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-60328191|title=Up where we belong! Graydon upsets the odds to take Walsall into Division One|date=19 May 1999|work=Birmingham Evening Mail|accessdate=5 July 2008}}</ref> After the unlikely promotion to the [[Football League Division One|second tier]] Walsall found life difficult at a higher level but battled right until the final day of the season, when relegation was finally sealed. A 2\u20130 defeat at [[Ipswich Town|Ipswich]] meant Walsall returned to the third tier, despite derby wins over local rivals Wolves, Birmingham and [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] earlier in the campaign. ''The Saddlers'' returned to the second tier of English football at the first attempt, defeating [[Reading FC|Reading]] 3\u20132, after extra time, in a thrilling play-off final at Cardiff's [[Millennium Stadium]].<ref name=\"Promotion 2001\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/1352124.stm|title=Walsall break Reading hearts|date=27 May 2001|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 July 2008}}</ref>\n\nGraydon was dismissed in January 2002 following a 2\u20130 defeat against local rivals West Brom. [[Colin Lee]] took over and secured survival in the second tier for the first time since the early 1960s. The [[2002\u201303 in English football|2002\u201303]] season saw Walsall avoid relegation again. However, the [[2003\u201304 in English football|2003\u201304]] campaign ended in relegation despite a storming start which had seen the club on the brink of the play-offs going into the New Year. A slump in form saw Lee sacked in April<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/walsall/3632301.stm|title=Walsall sack Lee|work=BBC Sport|date=16 April 2004|accessdate=9 August 2019}}</ref> and the appointment of star player [[Paul Merson]] as manager did not halt the slide. Walsall were ultimately relegated, agonisingly by a single goal, despite a 3\u20132 victory over Rotherham United on the season's final day in front of a record Bescot Stadium crowd of 11,049.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/walsall/4938122.stm|title=Walsall 3\u20132 Rotherham United|work=BBC Sport|date=9 May 2004|accessdate=9 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nDespite the club's relegation and no previous managerial experience, Merson was immediately appointed as full-time manager of the club in May 2004.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/merson-takes-permanent-managers-job-at-walsall-563035.html|title=Merson takes permanent manager's job at Walsall|work=The Independent|date=12 May 2004|accessdate=11 August 2019}}</ref> A poor season in [[League One]] almost ended in successive relegations and the [[2005\u201306 in English football|2005\u201306]] season then turned into a disastrous one for Walsall and Merson. After increasing supporter pressure following a string of bad results, culminating in a 5\u20130 defeat at [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]], Merson's reign as Walsall manager came to an end in February 2006.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/feb/07/newsstory.sport5|title=Merson sacked as struggling Walsall lose patience|date=7 February 2006|work=The Guardian|accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref> However, it was too late and Walsall were relegated on 22 April 2006, after losing 3\u20131 to [[Huddersfield Town]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/walsall/4938122.stm|title=Walsall sack manager Broadhurst|date=24 April 2006|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Richard Money]] was tasked with reviving the clubs fortunes in [[League Two]]. An impressive start to the season was maintained throughout and, despite a mini-blip in February, Walsall remained in the top three for almost the entire season and were promoted back to [[League One]] after beating [[Notts County]] 2\u20131 away from home.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/6534979.stm|title=Notts County 1-2 Walsall|date=14 April 2007|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref> On the final day of the season Walsall drew 1\u20131 at [[Swindon Town]], thanks to a last-minute goal by [[Dean Keates]] in front of 3,419 travelling fans, to secure the [[League Two]] title.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/6602935.stm|title=Swindon 1\u20131 Walsall|date=5 May 2007|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 July 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/west_midlands/6636873.stm|title=Promoted Walsall's open top tour |date=8 May 2007|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=5 July 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:WalsallvGills2009.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Walsall (in red shirts) playing [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]] in 2009 at Bescot Stadium]]\nWalsall's form continued into the new season, as the club performed strongly in [[2007\u201308 in English football|2007\u201308]], including a run of 17 League matches without defeat and back-to-back promotions looked possible. However, a January transfer window that culminated in the sales of important first team players [[Danny Fox]] and [[Scott Dann]] to [[Coventry City]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/scott-dann-follows-fox-to-coventry-57533|title=Scott Dann follows Fox to Coventry from Walsall|work=Birmingham Mail|date=1 February 2008|accessdate=11 August 2019}}</ref> caused a drop in form throughout 2008. The club's promotion challenge ended after a run of poor results in March leading to Richard Money resigning as manager in April.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2298077/Richard-Money-resigns-from-Walsall-post.html|title=Richard Money resigns from Walsall post|work=Telegraph|date=22 April 2008|accessdate=11 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe following seven seasons spent in League One saw largely mid-table security apart from a few flirtations with relegation. Notably, in the [[2010\u201311 in English football|2010\u201311 season]] the club sat in the relegation places from October through to March but ultimately survived thanks to an upturn in form following the appointment of [[Dean Smith (footballer, born 1971)|Dean Smith]] as manager in January 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/w/walsall/9369220.stm|title=Dean Smith gets Walsall job until end of season|work=BBC Sport|date=21 January 2011|accessdate=21 January 2011}}</ref> Walsall had been ten points adrift of safety, however, despite accumulating only 48 points by the end of the season they escaped relegation by one point.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/13247222|title=Southampton 3\u20131 Walsall|work=BBC Sport|date=7 May 2011|accessdate=9 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2014\u201315 in English football|2014\u201315 season]] was a memorable one for the club as it reached a [[Wembley Stadium|Wembley]] final for the first time in its 127-year history.<ref name=\"Wembley\">{{cite news|url=https://www.efl.com/news/2015/january/walsalls-wembley-near-misses/|title=Walsall's Wembley near-misses|date=28 January 2015|work=The Football League|accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref> Walsall beat [[Rochdale A.F.C.|Rochdale]], [[Tranmere Rovers]], [[Sheffield United]] and [[Preston North End]] on their way to the [[2015 Football League Trophy Final|Football League Trophy final]] where they were beaten 2\u20130 by Bristol City on Sunday 22 March 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/mar/22/bristol-city-walsall-johnstones-paint-trophy-match-report|title=Bristol City tick off their first objective with comfortable win over Walsall|date=22 March 2015|work=The Guardian|accessdate=11 August 2019}}</ref> ''The Saddlers'' were backed by over 29,000 supporters in a crowd of 72,315 at the national stadium.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/sport/football/walsall-fc/2015/03/12/walsall-release-1000-more-tickets-for-wembley/|title=Walsall release 1,000 more tickets for Wembley|work=Express and Star|date=12 March 2015|accessdate=9 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nWalsall started the [[2015\u201316 in English football|2015\u201316 season]] well, leading to interest in manager Dean Smith. At the end of November, with ''The Saddlers'' fourth in the table, he left Walsall for Brentford; at the time of his departure he was the fourth longest serving manager in the Football League.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fans react as Dean Smith leaves Walsall FC|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/sport/walsall-fc/2015/11/30/breaking-news-dean-smith-walsall-exit-imminent/|accessdate=30 November 2015|work=Express and Star|date=30 November 2015}}</ref> Walsall turned to [[Sean O'Driscoll]] to replace Smith.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/35132127|title=Sean O'Driscoll: Walsall name new head coach to replace Dean Smith|work=BBC Sport|date=18 December 2015|accessdate=19 December 2015}}</ref> However, after a six-game winless run and just 16 games in charge, O'Driscoll was sacked.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35739973|title=Sean O'Driscoll: Walsall part company with head coach after 16 games|date=6 March 2016|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 March 2016}}</ref> Ultimately, Walsall missed out on promotion by just one point and lost in the play-off semi-finals to Barnsley.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36273069|title=Walsall 1\u20133 Barnsley (1\u20136 agg)|work=BBC Sport|date=19 May 2016|accessdate=9 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the decimation of their promotion challenging team, Walsall struggled for the next three seasons in League One and, after a disastrous spell in charge for former playing hero Dean Keates, were relegated back to the fourth tier at the end of the [[2018\u201319 in English football|2018\u201319 season]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Walsall relegated to League Two after draw with Shrewsbury Town|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/sport/football/walsall-fc/2019/05/04/walsall-relegated-to-league-two-after-draw-with-shrewsbury-town/|work=Express and Star|date=4 May 2019|accessdate=9 August 2019}}</ref> Following relegation, a new era began with [[Darrell Clarke]] taking over as manager<ref>{{cite news|title=Walsall name ex-Bristol Rovers boss as new manager|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/48226786|work=BBC Sport|date=10 May 2019|accessdate=12 May 2019}}</ref> and Jeff Bonser ending his 28-year reign as owner and chairman by selling his 76% majority shareholding of the club to Leigh Pomlett in July 2019.<ref>{{cite news|title=Owner Jeff Bonser sells up after 28 years|url=https://www.expressandstar.com/sport/football/walsall-fc/2019/07/29/walsall-takeover-jeff-bonser-sells-up/|work=Express and Star|date=29 July 2019|accessdate=9 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==A timeline of Walsall's history==\n*1888&nbsp;\u2013 Founded as ''Walsall Town Swifts\n*1892&nbsp;\u2013 Founder Members of the [[Football League Second Division]].\n*1896&nbsp;\u2013 Renamed Walsall F.C.\n*1896&nbsp;\u2013 Move into the new Hillary Street Ground, which will later become known as [[Fellows Park]], Walsall's home, on and off, until 1990.\n*1901&nbsp;\u2013 Failed to gain re-election to the Football League.\n*1921&nbsp;\u2013 League football returns to Walsall after 20 years as the club become Founder Members of the [[Football League Third Division North]].\n*1933&nbsp;\u2013 Beat [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in the FA Cup, a result still regarded as one of the greatest FA Cup upsets of all-time.\n*1960&nbsp;\u2013 Win the Fourth Division title. The club's first league win in their history.\n*1961&nbsp;\u2013 Win second successive promotion to reach Second Division.\n*1963&nbsp;\u2013 Relegated back to Third Division where the club would spend 24 out of the next 25 seasons.\n*1972&nbsp;\u2013 Club rescued from financial oblivion by new owner Ken Wheldon.\n*1975&nbsp;\u2013 Defeat [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] in the FA Cup on the way to the fifth round.\n*1978&nbsp;\u2013 Defeat [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] in the FA Cup on the way to the fifth round.\n*1979&nbsp;\u2013 Sign striker [[Alan Buckley]] back from [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]], for a what was a club record of \u00a3175,000 until 2016.\n*1984&nbsp;\u2013 Reach the League Cup semi-finals, defeating Arsenal at Highbury in the fourth round.\n*1986&nbsp;\u2013 Racecourse owner Terry Ramsden buys the club.\n*1988&nbsp;\u2013 Promotion to the Second Division is achieved through the play-offs.\n*1989&nbsp;\u2013 Relegation to Third Division after just one season in the Second Division.\n*1990&nbsp;\u2013 A second successive relegation to the Fourth Division in time for the move to [[Bescot Stadium]], a few hundred yards from Fellows Park.\n*1992&nbsp;\u2013 Jeff Bonser buys the club, which again was minutes away from entering receivership.\n*1995&nbsp;\u2013 Win promotion to Division Two as runners-up.\n*1998&nbsp;\u2013 Reach the fourth round of the League Cup and FA Cup under [[Jan Sorensen]], who lasts only one season and is succeeded by [[Ray Graydon]].\n*1999&nbsp;\u2013 Win promotion to Division One as runners-up ahead of [[Manchester City]].\n*2000&nbsp;\u2013 Relegated back to Division Two, being pipped to survival by local rivals [[West Bromwich Albion]].\n*2001&nbsp;\u2013 Promoted to Division One at the first attempt, winning the Division Two play-offs.\n*2004&nbsp;\u2013 Relegated from Division One on goal difference.\n*2006&nbsp;\u2013 Two relegations in three seasons sees the club fall to League Two.\n*2007&nbsp;\u2013 Win the League Two title at the first attempt and are promoted back to League One.\n*2015&nbsp;\u2013 Reach the [[Football League Trophy]] final, play at [[Wembley Stadium]] for the first time in their history but lose 2\u20130 to [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]].\n*2019&nbsp;\u2013 Relegated to [[League Two]]. Bonser steps down, with director Leigh Pomlett taking over as chairman and majority shareholder.\n\n==Rivals==\n\nA 2013 survey revealed Walsall fans consider Black Country neighbours [[Wolverhampton Wanderers]] to be the club's main rivals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thechriswhitingshow.wordpress.com/2012/08/28/2012-football-rivalry-census-results/|title=2012-13 Football Rivalry Survey Results|work=The Chris Whiting Show|date=28 August 2012|accessdate=11 August 2019}}</ref> However, meetings between the teams are relatively rare, with Wolves having spent most of their existence in the top two tiers of English football. Only [[Black Country derby|16 competitive fixtures]] have been played between Walsall and Wolves, with the most recent occurring in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.11v11.com/teams/walsall/tab/opposingTeams/opposition/Wolverhampton%20Wanderers/|title=Walsall record v Wolverhampton Wanderers|work=11v11.com|accessdate=11 August 2019}}</ref> Meetings with the Black Country's other professional club, [[West Bromwich Albion]], are similarly rare, with ''The Saddlers'' and ''The Baggies'' having clashed just 14 times.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.11v11.com/teams/walsall/tab/opposingTeams/opposition/West%20Bromwich%20Albion/|title=Walsall record v West Bromwich Albion|work=11v11.com|accessdate=11 August 2019}}</ref> However, the Black Country rivals did meet on numerous occasions during wartime regionalised league fixtures.<ref name=\"HistoryBook\"/>\n\nMore regularly-contested rivalries exist with [[Shrewsbury Town]], [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] and [[Port Vale]]. All three clubs are often ''The Saddlers''' geographically-closest league fixtures. Walsall have the upper hand in the Shrewsbury and Port Vale rivalries, having won significantly more fixtures than they have lost.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.11v11.com/teams/walsall/tab/opposingTeams/opposition/Shrewsbury%20Town/|title=Walsall record v Shrewsbury Town|work=11v11.com|accessdate=11 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.11v11.com/teams/walsall/tab/opposingTeams/opposition/Coventry%20City/|title=Walsall record v Coventry City|work=11v11.com|accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.11v11.com/teams/walsall/tab/opposingTeams/opposition/Port%20Vale/|title=Walsall record v Port Vale|work=11v11.com|accessdate=11 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Grounds==\n\n===The Chuckery===\n\nThis multi-purpose sports ground was situated in a district near to the Walsall Arboretum. It comprised some 12 football pitches and four good-sized cricket squares. It was the first ever home ground for Walsall F.C. from 1888 until 1893.\n\n===West Bromwich Road===\n\nThe new ground in West Bromwich Road, which had a capacity of just over 4,500, proved to be a lucky omen for The Saddlers between 1893 and 1896.\n\n===Fellows Park===\n{{Main|Fellows Park}}\nFellows Park was a former football stadium in Walsall, England. It was the home ground of Walsall F.C. from 1896 until 1990, when the team moved to the [[Bescot Stadium]].\n\n===Bescot Stadium===\n{{Main|Bescot Stadium}}\nBescot Stadium, currently also known as Banks's Stadium for sponsorship purposes,<ref name=\"Walsall rename ground Banks's Stadium\">{{Cite news\n| title = Walsall rename ground Banks's Stadium\n| url = http://www.football-shirts.co.uk/fans/125\n| publisher=Football Shirts\n| date = 11 May 2007\n| accessdate =11 May 2007}}</ref> is the home ground of Walsall Football Club. It was built in 1989\u201390 at a cost of \u00a34.5m, replacing the club's previous ground, [[Fellows Park]], which was located a quarter of a mile away. The ground was opened by [[Sir Stanley Matthews]]. Upon Jeff Bonser stepping down from his role at the club, Leigh Pomlett agreed an option to reunite the saddlers with their stadium freehold \"in due time\".\n\n==Players==\n===Current squad===\n:{{updated|27 October 2019.}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.saddlers.co.uk/teams/first-team/|title=First Team|website=www.saddlers.co.uk|accessdate=31 July 2019}}</ref>''\n\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player |no=1  |nat=ENG |pos=GK |name=[[Liam Roberts]]}}\n{{Fs player |no=2  |nat=ENG |pos=DF |name=[[Cameron Norman]]}}\n{{Fs player |no=3  |nat=ENG |pos=DF |name=[[Cameron Pring]]|other=on loan from [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]}}\n{{Fs player |no=4  |nat=ENG |pos=DF |name=[[Mat Sadler]]}}\n{{Fs player |no=5  |nat=ENG |pos=DF |name=[[James Clarke (footballer, born 1989)|James Clarke]]|other=[[Captain (association football)|captain]]}}\n{{Fs player |no=6  |nat=ENG |pos=DF |name=[[Dan Scarr]]}}\n{{Fs player |no=7  |nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=[[Stuart Sinclair]]}}\n{{Fs player |no=8  |nat=IRE |pos=MF |name=[[Liam Kinsella]]}}\n{{Fs player |no=9  |nat=NIR |pos=FW |name=[[Caolan Lavery]]}}\n{{Fs player |no=10 |nat=ENG |pos=FW |name=[[Josh Gordon (footballer)|Josh Gordon]]}}\n{{Fs player |no=11 |nat=ENG |pos=FW |name=[[Elijah Adebayo]]}}\n{{Fs player |no=13 |nat=ENG |pos=GK |name=[[Jack Rose (footballer)|Jack Rose]]|other=on loan from [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]]}}\n{{Fs player |no=14 |nat=ENG |pos=DF |name=[[Kory Roberts]]}}\n{{Fs player |no=15 |nat=NIR |pos=FW |name=[[Rory Holden]]|other=on loan from [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]]}}\n{{Fs mid}}\n{{Fs player |no=16 |nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=[[Danny Guthrie]]}}\n{{fs player |no=17 |nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=[[James Hardy (footballer)|James Hardy]]}}\n{{fs player |no=18 |nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=[[Jack Kiersey]]}}\n{{Fs player |no=19 |nat=ENG |pos=FW |name=[[Mitchel Candlin]]}}\n{{Fs player |no=20 |nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=[[Alfie Bates]]}}\n{{Fs player |no=21 |nat=IRL |pos=DF |name=[[Callum Cockerill-Mollett]]}}\n{{Fs player |no=23 |nat=ENG |pos=DF |name=Tom Leak}}\n{{Fs player |no=24 |nat=ENG |pos=DF |name=[[Shay Facey]]}}\n{{Fs player |no=25 |nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=[[Wes McDonald]]}}\n{{Fs player |no=28 |nat=ENG |pos=FW |name=Luke Pearce}}\n{{Fs player |no=29 |nat=ENG |pos=MF |name=[[Jack Nolan (English footballer)|Jack Nolan]]}}\n{{Fs player |no=33 |nat=SCO |pos=DF |name=[[Zak Jules]]}}\n{{Fs player |no=34 |nat=ENG |pos=DF |name=[[Nathan Sheron]]|other=on loan from [[Fleetwood Town F.C.|Fleetwood Town]]}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n===Out on loan===\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player | no=22 | nat=ENG | pos=DF | name=Luke Little|other=on loan to [[Tamworth F.C.|Tamworth]]}}\n{{Fs player | no=26 | nat=ENG | pos=MF | name=[[Gary Liddle]]|other=on loan to [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]]}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n===Reserves and Youth===\n{{Main|Walsall F.C. Youth and Reserves}}\n\n==Management, Staff and Directors==\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===First Team===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Position !! Name\n|-\n|First Team Manager || {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Darrell Clarke]]\n|-\n|Assistant Coach || {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Marcus Stewart]]\n|-\n|Assistant Coach || {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Brian Dutton]]\n|-\n|Goalkeeping Coach ||  {{flagicon|NIR}} [[Maik Taylor]]\n|-\n|Strength & Conditioning Coach || {{flagicon|WAL}} [[Mark Bradley (footballer, born 1988)|Mark Bradley]]\n|-\n|Performance Analyst || {{flagicon|ENG}} Calum Hayes\n|-\n|Kit Man || {{flagicon|ENG}} Tom Bradley\n|-\n|Senior Physiotherapist || {{flagicon|ENG}} Marc Czuczman\n|}\n\n===Academy===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Position !! Name\n|-\n|Academy Manager || {{flagicon|ESP}} [[Miguel Llera]]\n|-\n|Professional Development Phase Coach || {{flagicon|ENG}} Kyle Kirby\n|-\n|Lead Youth Development Phase Coach || {{flagicon|ENG}} Ben King\n|-\n|Lead Foundation Phase Coach ||  {{flagicon|ENG}} Duane Allen\n|-\n|Head of Academy Coaching || {{flagicon|ENG}} Neil Harding\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Medical Staff===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Position !! Name\n|-\n|Club Doctor || {{flagicon|ENG}} Dr Chris Minton\n|-\n|Honorary Club Surgeon || {{flagicon|ENG}} Dr Ashven Pimpalnerkar\n|}\n\n===Directors===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Position !! Name\n|-\n|Chairman  || {{flagicon|ENG}} Leigh Pomlett\n|-\n|Chief Executive || {{flagicon|ENG}} Stefan Gamble\n|-\n|Club Secretary || {{flagicon|ENG}} Daniel Mole\n|-\n|Director ||  {{flagicon|ENG}} Nigel Bond\n|-\n|Director || {{flagicon|ENG}} Peter Gilman\n|-\n|Director || {{flagicon|ENG}} Richard Tisdale\n|-\n|Director || {{flagicon|ENG}} Roy Whalley\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n