ived: '''\u00a31,500,000''' \u2013 for [[Rico Henry]] from [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]], August 2016<ref>{{cite news|title=Rico Henry joins on a five-year deal from Walsall|url=https://www.brentfordfc.com/news/2016/august/rico-henry-joins-on-a-five-year-deal-from-walsall/|date=31 August 2016|work=Brentford F.C.|accessdate=21 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.saddlers.co.uk}}\n* [http://www.saddlers.co.uk/page/SaddlersAZIndex/0,,10428,00.html Saddlers A-Z, player biographies and appearance info&nbsp;\u2013 Official Site]\n* [http://www.wfcthevenue.co.uk// WFC The Venue]\n* [http://upthesaddlers.com/wp/ UpTheSaddlers&nbsp;\u2013 Forum]\n* [http://www.BescotBanter.net/ Bescot Banter&nbsp;\u2013 Latest news/views]\n\n{{Walsall F.C.}}\n{{EFL League Two}}\n{{Men's Football in the West Midlands}}\n\n[[Category:Walsall F.C.| ]]\n[[Category:1888 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1888]]\n[[Category:Sport in Walsall]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in the West Midlands (county)]]\n[[Category:Football clubs in England]]\n[[Category:Midland Football League (1889)]]\n[[Category:Southern Football League clubs]]\n[[Category:English Football League clubs]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7d:bf09:ff00:bc34:d64:fc55:4683", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walsall_F.C."}
{"title_page": "Mosman Park, Western Australia", "text_new": "{{About|a suburb of Perth, Western Australia|the local government area|Town of Mosman Park}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=March 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox Australian place | type = suburb\n|name=Mosman Park\n|city=Perth\n|state=wa\n|image=View of the Swan River and sign of Mosman Park, Western Australia.JPG\n|caption=View of the Swan River and sign of Mosman Park, Western Australia\n|lga=Town of Mosman Park\n| alternative_location_map = Australia Western Australia metropolitan Perth\n|coordinates = {{coord|32.016|S|115.762|E|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_label_position = left\n|area=4.3\n|postcode=6012\n|pop  =8,757 | pop_year = {{CensusAU|2016}}\n|pop_footnotes = <ref name=Census2016Y/>\n|dist1=11 | dir1 = SW\n|location1=[[Perth CBD]]\n|est=1890<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article3136057 |title=News and Notes |work=[[The West Australian]] |date=2 August 1890 |page=3 |accessdate=24 April 2014 }}</ref>\n|fedgov=[[Division of Curtin|Curtin]]\n|stategov=[[Electoral district of Cottesloe|Cottesloe]]\n|near-nw=[[Cottesloe, Western Australia|Cottesloe]]\n|near-n=[[Peppermint Grove, Western Australia|Peppermint Grove]]\n|near-ne=''[[Swan River (Western Australia)|Swan River]]''\n|near-w=[[Indian Ocean]]\n|near-e=''[[Swan River (Western Australia)|Swan River]]''\n|near-sw=[[North Fremantle, Western Australia|North Fremantle]]\n|near-s=''[[Swan River (Western Australia)|Swan River]]''\n|near-se=''[[Swan River (Western Australia)|Swan River]]''\n}}\n'''Mosman Park''' is a western suburb of [[Perth, Western Australia]] on the north bank of the [[Swan River (Western Australia)|Swan River]] in the [[Local government areas of Western Australia|local government area]] of the [[Town of Mosman Park]]. It was historically known as Buckland Hill (1889-1909), then Cottesloe Beach (1909-1930) and again Buckland Hill (1930-1937). From 1937 it was named Mosman Park, derived from [[Mosman, New South Wales|Mosman]] in Sydney, the birthplace of Richard Yeldon, a member of the Buckland Hill Road Board.<ref>{{cite web|title=Heritage Images|url=http://www.mosmanpark.wa.gov.au/community/history-of-mosman-park/heritage-images|website=Town of Mosman Park|accessdate=1 June 2016}}</ref> Mosman Park is now considered an affluent suburb, but prior to the 1970s was one of Perth's major industrial centres.\n\n==Geography==\nMosman Park is bounded by the [[Indian Ocean]] and the [[Fremantle railway line]] to the west, a line south of Johnston Street to the north, and the [[Swan River (Western Australia)|Swan River]] to the east and south with approximately 5&nbsp;km of river frontage. To the west of the railway line Mosman Park includes a section of approximately 600 metres of ocean frontage, south of the extension of Boundary Road and north of the extension of McCabe Street.\n\n==History==\nMosman Park was established with the first survey of town lots in 1889 as Buckland Hill, taking its name from the prominent local hill that was a major maritime navigation mark for shipping from the earliest days of colonization.<ref>{{cite news|title=Anchorage in Gage's Roads|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/65583996|accessdate=1 June 2016|work=The Inquirer|date=10 May 1843|location=Perth, WA|page=3}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Fremantle Municipal Council|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/66930607|accessdate=1 June 2016|work=The Inquirer and Commercial News|date=16 October 1889|location=Perth, WA}}</ref>\n\nMosman Park was a major industrial centre for the state with a [[GM Holden|General Motors]] car and truck assembly plant (1926-1972),<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article49877041 |title=G.M.-Holden Plans Big Programme |work=The West Australian |date=28 August 1951 |page=1 |accessdate=24 April 2014 }}</ref> the [[CSR Limited|Colonial Sugar Refinery]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article47637198 |title=Two Accidents at Factory |work=The West Australian |date=11 January 1949 |page=9 |accessdate=24 April 2014 }}</ref> the [[Mount Lyell Mining and Railway Company|Mt Lyell Farmers' Fertilisers]] superphosphate works,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article46312251 |title=Accidental Fatal Injury |work=The West Australian |date=16 May 1947 |page=19 |accessdate=24 April 2014 }}</ref> the  W.A. Rope and Twine Works<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article44823202 |title=Workers' Effort - Loan Representatives' Visits |work=The West Australian |date=2 October 1945 |page=4 |accessdate=24 April 2014 }}</ref> and the West Australian Brushware Co. factory (one of the largest of its kind in Australia).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article32798263 |title=Swan Brand Brushware |work=The West Australian |date=2 October 1934 |page=12 |accessdate=24 April 2014 }}</ref> All were closed by the 1970s. Today, almost all of Mosman Park is residential, with significant parklands at Buckland Hill and along the river.<ref>2006 S treetSmart directory, Department of Lands and Surveys, Perth.</ref>\n\nIn the {{CensusAU|2016}}, Mosman Park had a population of 8,757 people living in 4,064 private dwellings, 60.9% of which were detached houses on separate lots. The ABS identified health, hospitality and education as the main occupations of residents.<ref name=Census2016Y>{{Census 2016 AUS|id=LGA55740|name=Mosman Park (WA) (LGA) |accessdate=20 November 2017|quick=on}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nMosman Park is served by the [[Mosman Park railway station|Mosman Park]] and [[Victoria Street railway station, Perth|Victoria Street]] railway stations. Various public buses, including the [[CircleRoute]], travel along [[Stirling Highway]] and through Mosman Park's eastern section.\n\n==Politics==\nMosman Park is part of the federal division of [[Division of Curtin|Curtin]]. The federal seat is held by the [[Conservatism|conservative]] [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal Party]]. It is regarded as a safe seat as it has been continually retained by the [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal Party]] with the exception of former Liberal member [[Allan Rocher]] as an Independent politician between 1996 and 1998. For the parliament of Western Australia, the state electoral district of [[Electoral district of Cottesloe|Cottesloe]] is also held by the [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal Party]].\n\n==Notable residents==\n* [[Angela Bennett]], mining heiress and businesswoman \n* [[Lang Hancock]] (1909-1992), iron ore mining developer\n* [[Harriet Hooton]] (1875\u20131960), women's activist and editor\n* [[John Hughes (motor dealer)|John Hughes]], businessman\n* [[Rose Porteous]], widow of Lang Hancock\n* [[Ralph Sarich]], [[orbital engine]] and orbital combustion process inventor\n* [[Albert Wolff (judge)|Sir Albert Wolff]] (1899\u20131977), chief justice and lieutenant-governor of Western Australia\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Mosman Park, Western Australia}}\n* [http://www.mosmanpark.wa.gov.au/ Town of Mosman Park Website]\n\n{{Perth western suburbs}}\n\n[[Category:Suburbs of Perth, Western Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|a suburb of Perth, Western Australia|the local government area|Town of Mosman Park}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=March 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox Australian place | type = suburb\n|name=Mosman Park\n|city=Perth\n|state=wa\n|image=View of the Swan River and sign of Mosman Park, Western Australia.JPG\n|caption=View of the Swan River and sign of Mosman Park, Western Australia\n|lga=Town of Mosman Park\n| alternative_location_map = Australia Western Australia metropolitan Perth\n|coordinates = {{coord|32.016|S|115.762|E|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_label_position = left\n|area=4.3\n|postcode=6012\n|pop  =8,757 | pop_year = {{CensusAU|2016}}\n|pop_footnotes = <ref name=Census2016Y/>\n|dist1=11 | dir1 = SW\n|location1=[[Perth CBD]]\n|est=1890<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article3136057 |title=News and Notes |work=[[The West Australian]] |date=2 August 1890 |page=3 |accessdate=24 April 2014 }}</ref>\n|fedgov=[[Division of Curtin|Curtin]]\n|stategov=[[Electoral district of Cottesloe|Cottesloe]]\n|near-nw=[[Cottesloe, Western Australia|Cottesloe]]\n|near-n=[[Peppermint Grove, Western Australia|Peppermint Grove]]\n|near-ne=''[[Swan River (Western Australia)|Swan River]]''\n|near-w=[[Indian Ocean]]\n|near-e=''[[Swan River (Western Australia)|Swan River]]''\n|near-sw=[[North Fremantle, Western Australia|North Fremantle]]\n|near-s=''[[Swan River (Western Australia)|Swan River]]''\n|near-se=''[[Swan River (Western Australia)|Swan River]]''\n}}\n'''Mosman Park''' is a western suburb of [[Perth, Western Australia]] on the north bank of the [[Swan River (Western Australia)|Swan River]] in the [[Local government areas of Western Australia|local government area]] of the [[Town of Mosman Park]]. It was historically known as Buckland Hill (1889-1909), then Cottesloe Beach (1909-1930) and again Buckland Hill (1930-1937). From 1937 it was named Mosman Park, derived from [[Mosman, New South Wales|Mosman]] in Sydney, the birthplace of Richard Yeldon, a member of the Buckland Hill Road Board.<ref>{{cite web|title=Heritage Images|url=http://www.mosmanpark.wa.gov.au/community/history-of-mosman-park/heritage-images|website=Town of Mosman Park|accessdate=1 June 2016}}</ref> Mosman Park is now considered an affluent suburb, but prior to the 1970s was one of Perth's major industrial centres.\n\n==Geography==\nMosman Park is bounded by the [[Indian Ocean]] and the [[Fremantle railway line]] to the west, a line south of Johnston Street to the north, and the [[Swan River (Western Australia)|Swan River]] to the east and south with approximately 5&nbsp;km of river frontage. To the west of the railway line Mosman Park includes a section of approximately 600 metres of ocean frontage, south of the extension of Boundary Road and north of the extension of McCabe Street.\n\n==History==\nMosman Park was established with the first survey of town lots in 1889 as Buckland Hill, taking its name from the prominent local hill that was a major maritime navigation mark for shipping from the earliest days of colonization.<ref>{{cite news|title=Anchorage in Gage's Roads|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/65583996|accessdate=1 June 2016|work=The Inquirer|date=10 May 1843|location=Perth, WA|page=3}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Fremantle Municipal Council|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/66930607|accessdate=1 June 2016|work=The Inquirer and Commercial News|date=16 October 1889|location=Perth, WA}}</ref>\n\nMosman Park was a major industrial centre for the state with a [[GM Holden|General Motors]] car and truck assembly plant (1926-1972),<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article49877041 |title=G.M.-Holden Plans Big Programme |work=The West Australian |date=28 August 1951 |page=1 |accessdate=24 April 2014 }}</ref> the [[CSR Limited|Colonial Sugar Refinery]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article47637198 |title=Two Accidents at Factory |work=The West Australian |date=11 January 1949 |page=9 |accessdate=24 April 2014 }}</ref> the [[Mount Lyell Mining and Railway Company|Mt Lyell Farmers' Fertilisers]] superphosphate works,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article46312251 |title=Accidental Fatal Injury |work=The West Australian |date=16 May 1947 |page=19 |accessdate=24 April 2014 }}</ref> the  W.A. Rope and Twine Works<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article44823202 |title=Workers' Effort - Loan Representatives' Visits |work=The West Australian |date=2 October 1945 |page=4 |accessdate=24 April 2014 }}</ref> and the West Australian Brushware Co. factory (one of the largest of its kind in Australia).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article32798263 |title=Swan Brand Brushware |work=The West Australian |date=2 October 1934 |page=12 |accessdate=24 April 2014 }}</ref> All were closed by the 1970s. Today, almost all of Mosman Park is residential, with significant parklands at Buckland Hill and along the river.<ref>2006 S treetSmart directory, Department of Lands and Surveys, Perth.</ref>\n\nIn the {{CensusAU|2016}}, Mosman Park had a population of 8,757 people living in 4,064 private dwellings, 60.9% of which were detached houses on separate lots. The ABS identified health, hospitality and education as the main occupations of residents.<ref name=Census2016Y>{{Census 2016 AUS|id=LGA55740|name=Mosman Park (WA) (LGA) |accessdate=20 November 2017|quick=on}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nMosman Park is served by the [[Mosman Park railway station|Mosman Park]] and [[Victoria Street railway station, Perth|Victoria Street]] railway stations. Various public buses, including the [[CircleRoute]], travel along [[Stirling Highway]] and through Mosman Park's eastern section.\n\n==Politics==\nMosman Park is part of the federal division of [[Division of Curtin|Curtin]]. The federal seat is held by the [[Conservatism|conservative]] [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal Party]]. It is regarded as a safe seat as it has been continually retained by the [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal Party]] with the exception of former Liberal member [[Allan Rocher]] as an Independent politician between 1996 and 1998. For the parliament of Western Australia, the state electoral district of [[Electoral district of Cottesloe|Cottesloe]] is also held by the [[Liberal Party of Australia|Liberal Party]].\n\n==Notable residents==\n* [[Angela Bennett]], mining heiress and businesswoman \n* [[Lang Hancock]] (1909-1992), iron ore mining developer\n* [[Harriet Hooton]] (1875\u20131960), women's activist and editor\n* [[John Hughes (motor dealer)|John Hughes]], businessman\n* [[Rose Porteous]], widow of Lang Hancock\n* [[Ralph Sarich]], [[orbital engine]] and orbital combustion process inventor\n* [[Albert Wolff (judge)|Sir Albert Wolff]] (1899\u20131977), chief justice and lieutenant-governor of Western Australia\n* Peter Laurance [[Order of Australia|AO]], Officer in the Order of Australia (A.O.) and prominent Australian property developer as the founder of Pivot Group\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Mosman Park, Western Australia}}\n* [http://www.mosmanpark.wa.gov.au/ Town of Mosman Park Website]\n\n{{Perth western suburbs}}\n\n[[Category:Suburbs of Perth, Western Australia]]\n", "name_user": "Fleet Lists", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Undid revision 949388007 byFinn1122(talk)No article available to support nomination - was also nominated in a Sydney suburb)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mosman_Park,_Western_Australia"}
