l the 1983 World Cup matches]\n*[http://www.veoh.com/videos/v414976cFnFnfDt 1983 Final Highlights] video on Veoh\n*[http://www.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/WORLD_CUPS/WC83/ Cricket World Cup 1983] from [[Cricinfo]]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=equBRPDe0X4 West Indies v India 1983 World Cup Final] video on [https://www.youtube.com/ YouTube]\n\n{{1983 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{Cricket World Cup}}\n{{India Squad 1983 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{Lord's}}\n\n[[Category:1983 Cricket World Cup|Final, 1983 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in England]]\n[[Category:1983 in cricket|Cricket World Cup Final, 1983]]\n[[Category:1983 in English cricket|Cricket World Cup Final, 1983]]\n[[Category:International cricket competitions from 1980\u201381 to 1985]]\n[[Category:Cricket World Cup Finals]]\n[[Category:1983 sports events in London]]\n[[Category:International sports competitions in London|Cricket World Cup final]]\n[[Category:Lord's]]\n[[Category:Cricket in London]]\n\n[[es:Copa mundial de cr\u00edquet de 1983]]\n[[fr:Coupe du monde de cricket de 1983]]\n[[it:Coppa del Mondo di cricket 1983]]\n[[ml:\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d3f\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d31\u0d4d\u0d31\u0d4d \u0d32\u0d4b\u0d15\u0d15\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d4d 1983]]\n[[mr:\u0915\u094d\u0930\u093f\u0915\u0947\u091f \u0935\u093f\u0936\u094d\u0935\u091a\u0937\u0915, \u0967\u096f\u096e\u0969]]\n[[nl:Wereldkampioenschap cricket 1983]]\n[[pt:Copa do Mundo de Cr\u00edquete de 1983]]\n", "name_user": "Orenburg1", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1983_Cricket_World_Cup_Final"}
{"title_page": "Hanishi no Mimichi", "text_new": "'''Hanishi no Mimichi''' (\u571f\u5e2b\u6c34\u9053, \u571f\u5e2b\u6c0f\u5fa1\u9053 or \u571f\u5e2b\u6c34\u901a, also known by the [[courtesy name]] '''Hanishi no Shibimaro''' \u571f\u5e2b\u4e43\u5fd7\u5a62\u9ebf) was a Japanese [[kuge|nobleman]] and ''[[waka (poetry)|waka]]'' poet in the [[Nara period]].\n\n== Biography ==\nThe details of the life of the poet Hanishi no Mimichi are not well documented. Four poems in the famous ''[[waka (poetry)|waka]]'' anthology the ''[[Man'y\u014dsh\u016b]]'' are attributed to him, with his name being written in various styles in the notes attached to these poems.{{sfnm|1a1=Aso|1y=2006|1p=555|2a1=Nakanishi|2y=1985|2p=263}} His given name is written as \u6c34\u9053 (\"water-road\") in the attribution of poems 557 and 558 in Book IV, but at \u5fa1\u9053 (\"august-road\") for 843 in Book V.{{sfnm|1a1=Aso|1y=2006|1p=555}}\n\nHis ''[[kabane]]'' was [[Sukune]].{{sfnm|1a1=Aso|1y=2006|1p=555|2a1=Nakanishi|2y=1985|2p=263}}\n\nHis court position is not indicated in the collection, so he was likely of low rank.{{sfnm|1a1=Aso|1y=2006|1p=555}} The note attached to poem 3845 in Book XVI describes him as ''{{illm|\u014dtoneri|ja|\u5927\u820e\u4eba}}''.{{sfnm|1a1=Aso|1y=2006|1p=555|2a1=Nakanishi|2y=1985|2p=263}}\n\nIn [[Tenpy\u014d|Tenpy\u014d 2]] (730) he participated in a [[plum blossom]]-viewing party at the residence of [[\u014ctomo no Tabito]],{{sfnm|1a1=Nakanishi|1y=1985|1p=285}} then the governor (\u4e00\u5927\u5bb0\u5e25 ''ichi Dazai no sochi'') of the [[Dazaifu (government)|Dazaifu]].{{sfnm|1a1=Nakanishi|1y=1985|1p=285}}\n\n== Poetry ==\nPoems 557, 558, 843 and 3844 in the ''Man'y\u014dsh\u016b'' are attributed to him.{{sfnm|1a1=Nakanishi|1y=1985|1p=263}} The first pair of poems, included in Book V of the collection, were written on a sea voyage from his posting in [[Kyushu|Tsukushi]] to [[Nara, Nara|the capital]], expressing his pining for his feeling of loneliness without his wife and his desire to see her as soon as possible.{{sfnm|1a1=Aso|1y=2006|1p=554}} In his commentary on the poems, {{illm|Mizue Aso|ja|\u963f\u8607\u745e\u679d}} noted the use of taboo language, apparently deliberately so, to emphasize the sincerity of the poet's emotions.{{sfnm|1a1=Aso|1y=2006|1p=554}}\n{|align=center cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"border:1px solid black; background-color:#e7e8ff;\"\n|- align=center bgcolor=#d7a8ff\n|- \n!''Man'y\u014dgana''{{sfnm|1a1=Aso|1y=2006|1p=553|2a1=University of Virginia|2y=1999}}||Modern Japanese text{{sfnm|1a1=Aso|1y=2006|1p=553}}||Reconstructed Old Japanese{{citation needed|reason=Pretty sure Vovin includes this. Will check next time I'm in Asuka.|date=November 2019}}||Modern Japanese{{citation needed|reason=The spacing and hyphenation (or lack thereof) means this would be better taken from a reliable source.|date=November 2019}}||English translation{{citation needed|reason=Vovin and others have translated it. Will check next time I'm in Asuka. For now, a fairly literal Wikipedia-original translation.|date=November 2019}}\n|- valign=top\n|\n:\u5927\u8239\u4e4e\n:\u699c\u4e43\u9032\u5c13\n:\u78d0\u5c13\u89f8\n:\u8986\u8005\u8986\n:\u59b9\u5c13\u56e0\u800c\u8005\n|\n:\u5927\u8239\u3092\n:\u6f15\u304e\u306e\u9032\u307f\u306b\n:\u5ca9\u306b\u89e6\u308c\n:\u8986\u3089\u3070\u8986\u308c\n:\u59b9\u306b\u3088\u308a\u3066\u306f\n|\n:\n:\n:\n:\n:\n|\n:''\u014dfuna o''\n:''kogi no susumi ni''\n:''iwa ni fure''\n:''kaeraba kaere''\n:''imo ni yorite wa''\n|\n:As, in our great vessel,\n:we set sail out to sea,\n:if we should run into rocks and keel over\n:then let it be so if it means I can return the sooner,\n:that I can see my love again.\n|-\n|}\n{|align=center cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"border:1px solid black; background-color:#e7e8ff;\"\n|- align=center bgcolor=#d7a8ff\n|- \n!''Man'y\u014dgana''{{sfnm|1a1=Aso|1y=2006|1p=553|2a1=University of Virginia|2y=1999}}||Modern Japanese text{{sfnm|1a1=Aso|1y=2006|1p=553|2a1=University of Virginia|2y=1999}}||Reconstructed Old Japanese{{citation needed|reason=Pretty sure Vovin includes this. Will check next time I'm in Asuka.|date=November 2019}}||Modern Japanese{{citation needed|reason=The spacing and hyphenation (or lack thereof) means this would be better taken from a reliable source.|date=November 2019}}||English translation{{citation needed|reason=Vovin and others have translated it. Will check next time I'm in Asuka. For now, a fairly literal Wikipedia-original translation.|date=November 2019}}\n|- valign=top\n|\n:\u795e\u4e4b\u793e\u5c13\n:\u795e\u4e4b\u793e\u5c13\n:\u6211\u6302\u5e2b\n:\u5e63\u8005\u5c06\u8cdc\n:\u59b9\u5c13\u4e0d\u76f8\u570b\n|\n:\u3061\u306f\u3084\u3076\u308b\n:\u795e\u306e\u793e\u306b\n:\u308f\u304c\u61f8\u3051\u3057\n:\u5e63\u306f\u8cdc\u3089\u3080\n:\u59b9\u306b\u9022\u306f\u306a\u304f\u306b\n|\n:\n:\n:\n:\n:\n|\n:''chihayaburu''\n:''kami no yashiro ni''\n:''wa ga kakeshi''\n:''nusa wa tabaran''\n:''imo ni awanakuni''\n|\n:That offering I made\n:at the holy shrine\n:of the fierce and raging gods\u2014\n:I will be wanting it back,\n:for I was not able to meet my love.\n|-\n|}\n\nThe last of Mimichi's poems in the collection's ordering (which is not strictly chronological across books), 3844, is of uncertain date.{{sfnm|1a1=Nakamura|1y=2007|1p=278}} Akira Nakamura, in his article on Mimichi for the ''Man'y\u014dsh\u016b Kajin Jiten'' dates the poem to Mimichi's later years after returning to the Capital, based on stylistic differences with the earlier poems quoted above.{{sfnm|1a1=Nakamura|1y=2007|1p=279}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Reiwa]]\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Works cited ===\n{{Refbegin|colwidth=80em}}\n* {{cite book\n |last         = Aso\n |first        = Mizue\n |authorlink   = Mizue Aso<!-- https://ja.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/\u963f\u8607\u745e\u679d -->\n |title        = Man'y\u014dsh\u016b Zenka K\u014dgi (Kan Dai-san, Kan Dai-yon)\n |script-title = ja:\u842c\u8449\u96c6\u5168\u6b4c\u8b1b\u7fa9\uff08\u5dfb\u7b2c\u4e09\u3001\u5dfb\u7b2c\u56db\uff09\n |language     = Japanese\n |year         = 2006\n |volume       = 2\n |location     = Tokyo\n |publisher    = [[Kasama Shoin]]\n |oclc         = \n |ref          = harv\n |title-link   = Man'y\u014dsh\u016b Zenka K\u014dgi\n}}\n* {{cite book\n |last          = Nakamura\n |first         = Akira\n |author-link   = Akira Nakamura (scholar of Japanese literature)<!-- https://www.google.com/search?rlz=1C1SQJL_jaFR810FR810&sxsrf=ACYBGNSVaJavYGv1PuUzQweL0uOMnXnljA%3A1575083155200&ei=k9zhXZvoC8mRr7wPhOeA6Ao&q=%22%E4%B8%AD%E6%9D%91%E6%98%AD%22+%22%E4%B8%87%E8%91%89%22&oq=%22%E4%B8%AD%E6%9D%91%E6%98%AD%22+%22%E4%B8%87%E8%91%89%22&gs_l=psy-ab.3...2071.3756..5046...0.0..0.165.1657.0j12......0....1..gws-wiz.......38j0i67j0j0i7i4i30j0i4i37.n6iTZXWtxeU&ved=0ahUKEwjb_dP_-ZDmAhXJyIsBHYQzAK0Q4dUDCAs&uact=5 -->\n |chapter       = Hanishi no Sukune Mimichi\n |pages         = 278\u2013279\n |title         = Man'y\u014dsh\u016b Kajin Jiten\n |script-title  = ja:\u4e07\u8449\u96c6\u6b4c\u4eba\u4e8b\u5178\n |title-link    = Man'y\u014dsh\u016b Kajin Jiten\n |editor1-last  = \u014ckuma\n |editor1-first = Kiichir\u014d\n |editor1-link  = Kiichir\u014d \u014ckuma<!-- https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E5%A4%A7%E4%B9%85%E9%96%93%E5%96%9C%E4%B8%80%E9%83%8E -->\n |editor2-last  = Mori\n |editor2-first = Atsushi\n |editor2-link  = Atsushi Mori<!-- https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E6%A3%AE%E6%B7%B3%E5%8F%B8 -->\n |editor3-last  = Harihara\n |editor3-first = Takayuki\n |editor3-link  = Takayuki Harihara<!-- https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E9%87%9D%E5%8E%9F%E5%AD%9D%E4%B9%8B -->\n |language      = Japanese\n |year          = 2007\n |volume        = 1\n |location      = Tokyo\n |publisher     = [[Yuzankaku]]\n |isbn          = 978-4639019886\n |ref           = harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n |last         = Nakanishi\n |first        = Susumu\n |authorlink   = Susumu Nakanishi\n |year         = 1985\n |title        = Man'y\u014dsh\u016b Jiten (Man'y\u014dsh\u016b zen'yakuch\u016b genbun-tsuki bekkan)\n |publisher    = [[K\u014ddansha]]\n |location     = Tokyo\n |edition      = paperback\n |isbn         = 978-4-06-183651-8\n |ref          = harv\n}}\n* {{cite web\n |last         = University of Virginia\n |first        = \n |authorlink   = University of Virginia\n |year         = 1999\n |url          = http://jti.lib.virginia.edu/japanese/manyoshu/Man4Yos.html\n |title        = Manyoshu [Book 4]\n |publisher    = University of Virginia\n |location     = Charlottesville\n |ref          = harv\n |accessdate   = 2019-11-09\n}}\n{{Refend}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hanishi Mimichi}}\n\n[[Category:8th-century Japanese poets]]\n[[Category:Man'y\u014d poets]]\n[[Category:Japanese male poets]]\n[[Category:Kuge]]\n", "text_old": "'''Hanishi no Mimichi''' (\u571f\u5e2b\u6c34\u9053, \u571f\u5e2b\u6c0f\u5fa1\u9053 or \u571f\u5e2b\u6c34\u901a, also known by the [[courtesy name]] '''Hanishi no Shibimaro''' \u571f\u5e2b\u4e43\u5fd7\u5a62\u9ebf) was a Japanese [[kuge|nobleman]] and ''[[waka (poetry)|waka]]'' poet in the [[Nara period]].\n\n== Biography ==\nThe details of the life of the poet Hanishi no Mimichi are not well documented. Four poems in the famous ''[[waka (poetry)|waka]]'' anthology the ''[[Man'y\u014dsh\u016b]]'' are attributed to him, with his name being written in various styles in the notes attached to these poems.{{sfnm|1a1=Aso|1y=2006|1p=555|2a1=Nakanishi|2y=1985|2p=263}} His given name is written as \u6c34\u9053 (\"water-road\") in the attribution of poems 557 and 558 in Book IV, but at \u5fa1\u9053 (\"august-road\") for 843 in Book V.{{sfnm|1a1=Aso|1y=2006|1p=555}}\n\nHis ''[[kabane]]'' was [[Sukune]].{{sfnm|1a1=Aso|1y=2006|1p=555|2a1=Nakanishi|2y=1985|2p=263}}\n\nHis court position is not indicated in the collection, so he was likely of low rank.{{sfnm|1a1=Aso|1y=2006|1p=555}} The note attached to poem 3845 in Book XVI describes him as ''{{illm|\u014dtoneri|ja|\u5927\u820e\u4eba}}''.{{sfnm|1a1=Aso|1y=2006|1p=555|2a1=Nakanishi|2y=1985|2p=263}}\n\nIn [[Tenpy\u014d|Tenpy\u014d 2]] (730) he participated in a [[plum blossom]]-viewing party at the residence of [[\u014ctomo no Tabito]],{{sfnm|1a1=Nakanishi|1y=1985|1p=285}} then the governor (\u4e00\u5927\u5bb0\u5e25 ''ichi Dazai no sochi'') of the [[Dazaifu (government)|Dazaifu]].{{sfnm|1a1=Nakanishi|1y=1985|1p=285}}\n\n== Poetry ==\nPoems 557, 558, 843 and 3844 in the ''Man'y\u014dsh\u016b'' are attributed to him.{{sfnm|1a1=Nakanishi|1y=1985|1p=263}} The first pair of poems, included in Book V of the collection, were written on a sea voyage from his posting in [[Kyushu|Tsukushi]] to [[Nara, Nara|the capital]], expressing his pining for his feeling of loneliness without his wife and his desire to see her as soon as possible.{{sfnm|1a1=Aso|1y=2006|1p=554}} In his commentary on the poems, {{illm|Mizue Aso|ja|\u963f\u8607\u745e\u679d}} noted the use of taboo language, apparently deliberately so, to emphasize the sincerity of the poet's emotions.{{sfnm|1a1=Aso|1y=2006|1p=554}}\n{|align=center cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"border:1px solid black; background-color:#e7e8ff;\"\n|- align=center bgcolor=#d7a8ff\n|- \n!''Man'y\u014dgana''{{sfnm|1a1=Aso|1y=2006|1p=553|2a1=University of Virginia|2y=1999}}||Modern Japanese text{{sfnm|1a1=Aso|1y=2006|1p=553}}||Reconstructed Old Japanese{{citation needed|reason=Pretty sure Vovin includes this. Will check next time I'm in Asuka.|date=November 2019}}||Modern Japanese{{citation needed|reason=The spacing and hyphenation (or lack thereof) means this would be better taken from a reliable source.|date=November 2019}}||English translation{{citation needed|reason=Vovin and others have translated it. Will check next time I'm in Asuka. For now, a fairly literal Wikipedia-original translation.|date=November 2019}}\n|- valign=top\n|\n:\u5927\u8239\u4e4e\n:\u699c\u4e43\u9032\u5c13\n:\u78d0\u5c13\u89f8\n:\u8986\u8005\u8986\n:\u59b9\u5c13\u56e0\u800c\u8005\n|\n:\u5927\u8239\u3092\n:\u6f15\u304e\u306e\u9032\u307f\u306b\n:\u5ca9\u306b\u89e6\u308c\n:\u8986\u3089\u3070\u8986\u308c\n:\u59b9\u306b\u3088\u308a\u3066\u306f\n|\n:''\n:''\n:''\n:''\n:''''\n|\n:''\u014dfuna o\n:''kogi no susumi ni\n:''iwa ni fure\n:''kaeraba kaere\n:''imo ni yorite wa''\n|\n:As, in our great vessel,\n:we set sail out to sea,\n:if we should run into rocks and keel over\n:then let it be so if it means I can return the sooner,\n:that I can see my love again.\n|-\n|}\n{|align=center cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"border:1px solid black; background-color:#e7e8ff;\"\n|- align=center bgcolor=#d7a8ff\n|- \n!''Man'y\u014dgana''{{sfnm|1a1=Aso|1y=2006|1p=553|2a1=University of Virginia|2y=1999}}||Modern Japanese text{{sfnm|1a1=Aso|1y=2006|1p=553|2a1=University of Virginia|2y=1999}}||Reconstructed Old Japanese{{citation needed|reason=Pretty sure Vovin includes this. Will check next time I'm in Asuka.|date=November 2019}}||Modern Japanese{{citation needed|reason=The spacing and hyphenation (or lack thereof) means this would be better taken from a reliable source.|date=November 2019}}||English translation{{citation needed|reason=Vovin and others have translated it. Will check next time I'm in Asuka. For now, a fairly literal Wikipedia-original translation.|date=November 2019}}\n|- valign=top\n|\n:\u795e\u4e4b\u793e\u5c13\n:\u795e\u4e4b\u793e\u5c13\n:\u6211\u6302\u5e2b\n:\u5e63\u8005\u5c06\u8cdc\n:\u59b9\u5c13\u4e0d\u76f8\u570b\n|\n:\u3061\u306f\u3084\u3076\u308b\n:\u795e\u306e\u793e\u306b\n:\u308f\u304c\u61f8\u3051\u3057\n:\u5e63\u306f\u8cdc\u3089\u3080\n:\u59b9\u306b\u9022\u306f\u306a\u304f\u306b\n|\n:''\n:''\n:''\n:''\n:''''\n|\n:''chihayaburu\n:''kami no yashiro ni\n:''wa ga kakeshi\n:''nusa wa tabaran\n:''imo ni awanakuni''\n|\n:That offering I made\n:at the holy shrine\n:of the fierce and raging gods\u2014\n:I will be wanting it back,\n:for I was not able to meet my love.\n|-\n|}\n\nThe last of Mimichi's poems in the collection's ordering (which is not strictly chronological across books), 3844, is of uncertain date.{{sfnm|1a1=Nakamura|1y=2007|1p=278}} Akira Nakamura, in his article on Mimichi for the ''Man'y\u014dsh\u016b Kajin Jiten'' dates the poem to Mimichi's later years after returning to the Capital, based on stylistic differences with the earlier poems quoted above.{{sfnm|1a1=Nakamura|1y=2007|1p=279}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Reiwa]]\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Works cited ===\n{{Refbegin|colwidth=80em}}\n* {{cite book\n |last         = Aso\n |first        = Mizue\n |authorlink   = Mizue Aso<!-- https://ja.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/\u963f\u8607\u745e\u679d -->\n |title        = Man'y\u014dsh\u016b Zenka K\u014dgi (Kan Dai-san, Kan Dai-yon)\n |script-title = ja:\u842c\u8449\u96c6\u5168\u6b4c\u8b1b\u7fa9\uff08\u5dfb\u7b2c\u4e09\u3001\u5dfb\u7b2c\u56db\uff09\n |language     = Japanese\n |year         = 2006\n |volume       = 2\n |location     = Tokyo\n |publisher    = [[Kasama Shoin]]\n |oclc         = \n |ref          = harv\n |title-link   = Man'y\u014dsh\u016b Zenka K\u014dgi\n}}\n* {{cite book\n |last          = Nakamura\n |first         = Akira\n |author-link   = Akira Nakamura (scholar of Japanese literature)<!-- https://www.google.com/search?rlz=1C1SQJL_jaFR810FR810&sxsrf=ACYBGNSVaJavYGv1PuUzQweL0uOMnXnljA%3A1575083155200&ei=k9zhXZvoC8mRr7wPhOeA6Ao&q=%22%E4%B8%AD%E6%9D%91%E6%98%AD%22+%22%E4%B8%87%E8%91%89%22&oq=%22%E4%B8%AD%E6%9D%91%E6%98%AD%22+%22%E4%B8%87%E8%91%89%22&gs_l=psy-ab.3...2071.3756..5046...0.0..0.165.1657.0j12......0....1..gws-wiz.......38j0i67j0j0i7i4i30j0i4i37.n6iTZXWtxeU&ved=0ahUKEwjb_dP_-ZDmAhXJyIsBHYQzAK0Q4dUDCAs&uact=5 -->\n |chapter       = Hanishi no Sukune Mimichi\n |pages         = 278\u2013279\n |title         = Man'y\u014dsh\u016b Kajin Jiten\n |script-title  = ja:\u4e07\u8449\u96c6\u6b4c\u4eba\u4e8b\u5178\n |title-link    = Man'y\u014dsh\u016b Kajin Jiten\n |editor1-last  = \u014ckuma\n |editor1-first = Kiichir\u014d\n |editor1-link  = Kiichir\u014d \u014ckuma<!-- https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E5%A4%A7%E4%B9%85%E9%96%93%E5%96%9C%E4%B8%80%E9%83%8E -->\n |editor2-last  = Mori\n |editor2-first = Atsushi\n |editor2-link  = Atsushi Mori<!-- https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E6%A3%AE%E6%B7%B3%E5%8F%B8 -->\n |editor3-last  = Harihara\n |editor3-first = Takayuki\n |editor3-link  = Takayuki Harihara<!-- https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E9%87%9D%E5%8E%9F%E5%AD%9D%E4%B9%8B -->\n |language      = Japanese\n |year          = 2007\n |volume        = 1\n |location      = Tokyo\n |publisher     = [[Yuzankaku]]\n |isbn          = 978-4639019886\n |ref           = harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n |last         = Nakanishi\n |first        = Susumu\n |authorlink   = Susumu Nakanishi\n |year         = 1985\n |title        = Man'y\u014dsh\u016b Jiten (Man'y\u014dsh\u016b zen'yakuch\u016b genbun-tsuki bekkan)\n |publisher    = [[K\u014ddansha]]\n |location     = Tokyo\n |edition      = paperback\n |isbn         = 978-4-06-183651-8\n |ref          = harv\n}}\n* {{cite web\n |last         = University of Virginia\n |first        = \n |authorlink   = University of Virginia\n |year         = 1999\n |url          = http://jti.lib.virginia.edu/japanese/manyoshu/Man4Yos.html\n |title        = Manyoshu [Book 4]\n |publisher    = University of Virginia\n |location     = Charlottesville\n |ref          = harv\n |accessdate   = 2019-11-09\n}}\n{{Refend}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hanishi Mimichi}}\n\n[[Category:8th-century Japanese poets]]\n[[Category:Man'y\u014d poets]]\n[[Category:Japanese male poets]]\n[[Category:Kuge]]\n", "name_user": "WOSlinker", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix italics", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hanishi_no_Mimichi"}
{"title_page": "The Repentant", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|2012 film}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Repentant\n| image          = Affiche 210 Le repenti Fr.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Merzak Allouache]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = Merzak Allouache\n| starring       = [[Ali Mahfiche]] <br> [[Xavier Thibault]] <br> [[Carole Verner]] <br> [[Julien Perez]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = Mohamed Tayeb Laggoune\n| editing        =  [[Sylvie Gadmer]]\n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|2012|5|18|[[2012 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]]|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 87 minutes\n| country        = Algeria\n| language       = Arabic\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''The Repentant''''' ({{lang-ar|El Taaib}}) is a 2012 Algerian [[drama film]] directed by [[Merzak Allouache]]. It was screened in the [[Directors' Fortnight]] section at the [[2012 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Leffler|first=Rebecca|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/michel-gondry-cannes-film-festival-directors-fortnight-314985|title=Cannes 2012: Michel Gondry\u2019s 'The We & The I' to Open Director's Fortnight|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=26 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.quinzaine-realisateurs.com/2012-selection-h201.html|title=2012 Selection|work=quinzaine-realisateurs.com|publisher=[[Directors' Fortnight]]|accessdate=26 May 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426224019/http://www.quinzaine-realisateurs.com/2012-selection-h201.html|archivedate=26 April 2012}}</ref> The film won the [[FIPRESCI]] Award for Best Asian Film at the [[International Film Festival of Kerala#IFFK 2012|17th International Film Festival of Kerala]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://english.manoramaonline.com/cgi-bin/MMOnline.dll/portal/ep/contentView.do?contentId=13032215&tabId=1&programId=11565535|title=Curtains down on IFFK, Sta. Nina bags Suvarna Chakoram|work=[[Malayala Manorama]]|date=14 December 2012|accessdate=14 December 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130111052013/http://english.manoramaonline.com/cgi-bin/MMOnline.dll/portal/ep/contentView.do?contentId=13032215&tabId=1&programId=11565535|archivedate=11 January 2013}}</ref> The film was inspired by a true story.\n\n==Plot==\nIn the high flatlands  of Algeria, Islamic terrorists continue to spread terror. Rashid, a young [[Jihadism|jihadist]] leaves the mountains to return to his village. In keeping with the law of \"pardon and national harmony\", he has to surrender to the police and give up his weapon. He thus receives amnesty and becomes a \"repenti\". He is given a job in a caf\u00e9 and a place to live. But the law cannot erase his crimes, and for Rashid, it is the beginning of a one way journey of violence, secrets and manipulation. He attempts to atone for his crimes by giving closure to a family that his \"brothers\" hurt. Not everyone is as thrilled by Rachid's return as his parents, and some of the men from his village accuse him of having been at a massacre where their families were killed. Rachid denies having been there, but they do not all believe him. One of the men attacks Rachid one night. Rachid fights back, and ends up killing the man with his knife. The police investigate his disappearance and the murder.\n\nLakhdar is a pharmacist in the same neighborhood where Rachid works. He receives a shocking and mysterious call which prompts him to call his estranged wife back to town. Even once she returns, they are distant and both in great emotional pain. They impatiently await another call from the mystery caller, which finally leads them on a journey to the mountains, still inhabited by terrorists, to get closure from the trauma that drove them apart. Lakhdar's wife is very angry with Rachid, and yells at him for making them pay for closure on the trauma that she accuses him of having caused them. He once again denies involvement, saying that he only heard the story of what had happened and not participated, adding that those responsible had died a month later. This does nothing to alleviate the loss that she feels.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Nabil Asli]] as Rashid\n* [[Adila Bendimerad]]\n* [[Khaled Benaissa]] as Lakhdar\n\n==Awards==\n2012 [[IFFK|17th International Film Festival of Kerala]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Thiruvananthapuram/suvarna-chakoram-for-sta-nina/article4202911.ece|title=Suvarna Chakoram for Sta. Nina|work=The Hindu|accessdate=15 December 2012}}</ref>\n*the [[FIPRESCI]] Award for Best Asian Film \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|2399515|The Repentant}}\n\n{{Merzak Allouache}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Repentant}}\n[[Category:2012 films]]\n[[Category:2010s drama films]]\n[[Category:Algerian films]]\n[[Category:Arabic-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Merzak Allouache]]\n[[Category:Algerian drama films]]\n{{Algeria-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{short description|2012 film}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Repentant\n| image          = Affiche 210 Le repenti Fr.jpg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Merzak Allouache]]\n| producer       = \n| writer         = Merzak Allouache\n| starring       = [[Ali Mahfiche]] <br> [[Xavier Thibault]] <br> [[Carole Verner]] <br> [[Julien Perez]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = Mohamed Tayeb Laggoune\n| editing        =  [[Sylvie Gadmer]]\n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{Film date|2012|5|18|[[2012 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]]|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 87 minutes\n| country        = Algeria\n| language       = Arabic\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''The Repentant''''' ({{lang-ar|El Taaib}}) is a 2012 Algerian [[drama film]] directed by [[Merzak Allouache]]. It was screened in the [[Directors' Fortnight]] section at the [[2012 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Leffler|first=Rebecca|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/michel-gondry-cannes-film-festival-directors-fortnight-314985|title=Cannes 2012: Michel Gondry\u2019s 'The We & The I' to Open Director's Fortnight|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=26 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.quinzaine-realisateurs.com/2012-selection-h201.html|title=2012 Selection|work=quinzaine-realisateurs.com|publisher=[[Directors' Fortnight]]|accessdate=26 May 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426224019/http://www.quinzaine-realisateurs.com/2012-selection-h201.html|archivedate=26 April 2012}}</ref> The film won the [[FIPRESCI]] Award for Best Asian Film at the [[International Film Festival of Kerala#IFFK 2012|17th International Film Festival of Kerala]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://english.manoramaonline.com/cgi-bin/MMOnline.dll/portal/ep/contentView.do?contentId=13032215&tabId=1&programId=11565535|title=Curtains down on IFFK, Sta. Nina bags Suvarna Chakoram|work=[[Malayala Manorama]]|date=14 December 2012|accessdate=14 December 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130111052013/http://english.manoramaonline.com/cgi-bin/MMOnline.dll/portal/ep/contentView.do?contentId=13032215&tabId=1&programId=11565535|archivedate=11 January 2013}}</ref> The film was inspired by a true story.\n\n==Plot==\nIn the high flatlands  of Algeria, Islamic terrorists continue to spread terror. Rashid, a young [[Jihadism|jihadist]] leaves the mountains to return to his village. In keeping with the law of \"pardon and national harmony\", he has to surrender to the police and give up his weapon. He thus receives amnesty and becomes a \"repenti\". He is given a job in a caf\u00e9 and a place to live. But the law cannot erase his crimes, and for Rashid, it is the beginning of a one way journey of violence, secrets and manipulation. He attempts to atone for his crimes by giving closure to a family that his \"brothers\" hurt. Not everyone is as thrilled by Rachid's return as his parents, and some of the men from his village accuse him of having been at a massacre where their families were killed. Rachid denies having been there, but they do not all believe him. One of the men attacks Rachid one night. Rachid fights back, and ends up killing the man with his knife. The police investigate his disappearance and the murder.\n\nLakhdar is a pharmacist in the same neighborhood where Rachid works. He receives a shocking and mysterious call which prompts him to call his estranged wife back to town. Even once she returns, they are distant and both in great emotional pain. They impatiently await another call from the mystery caller, which finally leads them on a journey to the mountains, still inhabited by terrorists, to get closure from the trauma that drove them apart. Lakhdar's wife is very angry with Rachid, and yells at him for making them pay for closure on the trauma that she accuses him of having caused them. He once again denies involvement, saying that he only heard the story of what had happened and not participated, adding that those responsible had died a month later. This does nothing to alleviate the loss that she feels.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Nabil Asli]] as Rashid\n* [[Adila Bendimerad]]\n* [[Khaled Benaissa]] as Lakhdar\n\n==Awards==\n2012 [[IFFK|17th International Film Festival of Kerala]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Thiruvananthapuram/suvarna-chakoram-for-sta-nina/article4202911.ece|title=Suvarna Chakoram for Sta. Nina|work=The Hindu|accessdate=15 December 2012}}</ref>\n*the [[FIPRESCI]] Award for Best Asian Film \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|2399515|The Repentant}}\n\n{{Merzak Allouache}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Repentant}}\n[[Category:2012 films]]\n[[Category:2010s drama films]]\n[[Category:Algerian films]]\n[[Category:Arabic-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Merzak Allouache]]\n[[Category:Algerian drama films]]\n{{Algeria-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Repentant"}
